  "named_answer": "b",
  "named_answer_justification": "No single knob moved E2E by >= +5% above the 142298 ops/s baseline. Max upward delta = +0.00% (within run variance). Largest downward = -10.83%. Broker JMX `RequestHandlerAvgIdlePercent` averaged 2.60 across all experiments (with 3 in-process brokers in the JVM, that's ~87% spare capacity per broker), meaning the broker handler pool is HIGHLY IDLE and is NOT the bottleneck. Combined with Phase 6's 96.81% leader-record-wall named coverage, the cap appears to be on the AA leader thread / per-record overhead path that is unaffected by Kafka client-side or broker-side thread tuning. Phase 6 named answer (b) is validated insofar as Kafka client tuning does not move the cap; the deeper cap source is on the AA leader hot path.",
  "broker_jmx_summary": {
    "handler_idle_pct_avg_across_experiments": 2.598333333333333,
    "interpretation": "RequestHandlerAvgIdlePercent is a yammer Meter measuring idle thread-time per second summed across the request-handler thread pool. With 3 in-process brokers (parent + 2 child regions) in the same JVM, the platform MBeanServer reports the value summed across them; ~2.5-2.8 indicates roughly 0.83-0.93 per broker, i.e. brokers are 83-93% idle on the request-handler dimension. Coupled with broker `produce_total_ms < 0.25 ms` (near-zero broker write latency), the in-process broker has substantial CPU headroom for the AA workload."
  },
